-Haytham</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Book_of_Optics" title="Book of Optics">Book of Optics</a></i> (<i>Kitab al-Manazir</i>)&#160;– was undoubtedly prompted by Arabic sources. The proofs put forward in the fourteenth century by the Jewish scholar <a href="/wiki/Levi_ben_Gerson" class="mw-redirect" title="Levi ben Gerson">Levi ben Gerson</a>, who lived in southern France, and by the above-mentioned Alfonso from Spain directly border on Ibn al-Haytham's demonstration. Above, we have demonstrated that <i>Pseudo-Tusi's Exposition of Euclid</i> had stimulated both J. Wallis's and G. <a href="/wiki/Saccheri" class="mw-redirect" title="Saccheri">Saccheri</a>'s studies of the theory of parallel lines."</p></blockquote></span>
